#Problem is that every question is its own column - these questions are values of the variable question_item! Need to be pivot_longer() into new dataframe. 

patient_satisfaction_tidy <- patient_satisfaction_raw %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = `satisfaction in RM`:`parking, playing rooms, caffes`,
               names_to = "question_item",
               values_to = "response")

#inspect tidy data

#### COUNT()
patient_satisfaction_count <- patient_satisfaction_tidy %>% 
  count(question_item,response) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(n = ifelse(response >2, n ,-n))

#### PERCENTAGE()------------------------------------------------------------------
patient_satisfaction_percentage <- patient_satisfaction_tidy %>% 
  filter(!is.na(response)) %>% 
  group_by(question_item,response) %>% 
  summarize(n = n()) %>% 
  mutate(total = sum(n),
         percentage = n/total,
         response = factor(response))

Data Visualization

Questions: What is the distribution of responses across different aspects of the service provided? Which service shows higher satisfaction? Which shows lower satisfaction?

Draw two (2) different plots to answer these questions. I will consider this completed if you are able to interpret your plots in a way to answer the three questions above.

BAR PLOT: Response Total Count

patient_satisfaction_count %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n,
             y = reorder(question_item,-n),
             fill=factor(response)),
         colour = "black")+
  geom_col(data = patient_satisfaction_count %>% filter( n > 0), 
           position = position_stack(reverse = TRUE),
           color = "black",
           size = 0.5) +
  geom_col(data = patient_satisfaction_count %>% filter( n < 1),
           position = position_stack(reverse = FALSE),
           color="black",
           size = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = brewer.pal(5, "RdBu")) + 
  theme_grey()+
  labs(x = "Total(n)",
       y= "",
       fill = "Response",
       title = "Patient Satisfaction Survey",
       subtitle = "in Macedonia",
       caption = "data from Kaggle.com"
  )

BAR PLOT: Distribution of Responses

patient_satisfaction_percentage %>%
  # facet_arrange arranges all subplots by percentage of response==1
  mutate(facet_arrange = ifelse(response==1,percentage,0)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=response,
         y=percentage,
         fill=response,))+
  geom_col(color = "black", size = 0.5)+
  geom_text(aes(label=round(percentage,2)),
            colour = 'black',
            fontface = "plain",
            size = 4,
            vjust = -0.5,
            position = position_stack(vjust = 1))+
  scale_fill_manual(values = brewer.pal(5, "RdBu")) + 
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0,1)))+
  facet_wrap(facets = ~reorder(question_item,-facet_arrange),ncol=2)+
  theme_grey()+
  labs(x="",
       y = "Percentage",
       fill = "Response",
       title="Patient Satisfaction Survey",
       subtitle= "Broken Down By Question",
       caption = "data from Kaggle.com")+
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 16),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 18),
        strip.text = element_text(size = 16),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 24),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 18),
        plot.caption = element_text(size = 16),
        strip.placement = "outside"
  )

Further exploration.

patient_satisfaction_condensed <- patient_satisfaction_percentage %>% 
  mutate(response = as.numeric(response)) %>% 
  mutate(ranking = case_when(response <3 ~"bad",
                             response >3 ~"good",
                             response == 3~"neutral"))

patient_satisfaction_condensed <- patient_satisfaction_condensed %>% 
  group_by(question_item,ranking) %>% 
  summarize(percent = sum(percentage))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'question_item'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
patient_satisfaction_condensed %>%
  # facet_arrange arranges all subplots by percentage of response==1
  mutate(ranking_arrange = ifelse(ranking=="bad",percent,0)) %>%
  # explicit ordering of x axis
  mutate(ranking = factor(ranking, levels = c("bad", "neutral", "good"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= ranking,
         y=percent,
         fill=ranking,))+
  geom_col(color = "black", size = 0.5)+
  geom_text(aes(label=round(percent,2)),
            colour = 'black',
            fontface = "plain",
            size = 4,
            vjust = -0.5,
            position = position_stack(vjust = 1))+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#EF3535","#F1F1F1","#40BF37")) + 
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0,1)))+
  facet_wrap(facets = ~reorder(question_item,-ranking_arrange),ncol=2)+
  theme_grey()+
  labs(x='',
       y = "Percentage",
       fill = "Response Type",
       title="Patient Satisfaction Survey",
       subtitle = "Assuming Likert Scale Responses",
       caption = "data from Kaggle.com") +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 16),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 18),
        strip.text = element_text(size = 16),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 24),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 18),
        plot.caption = element_text(size = 16),
        strip.placement = "outside"
  )

ENTER YOUR INTERPRETATION TO THE PLOT YOU CREATED HERE

What is the distribution of responses across different aspects of the service provided? Which service shows higher satisfaction? Which shows lower satisfaction?

Q1) For the majority of questions, the distribution has all response types recognized, with responses of 5 being the rarest. The only question that does not have a response type of 5, or even 4, is the last service question on graph 1: Satisfication in RM.

Q2 & Q3) If only using graph 1, it would appear that Satisfication in RM would have the highest level of satisfaction and Modern equipment would have the lowest. However, looking at graph 2, which is the response type percentage breakdown for each question, I highly doubt Satisfaction in RM has the highest level of satisfaction - it didnt have a single 4 or 5 response!

Looking at the data again, we see that all responses are a number from 1-5. This highly suggests the use of a Likert scale. Additionally, this is an odd number scale, meaning the middle number, 3, is mostly like interpreted as neutral. Assuming these details, I created a third graph condensing the response types into three groups: bad (response < 3), neutral (response == 3), and good (response > 3).

According to the third graph, Satisfication in RM has the lowest level of satisfaction with bad being 55% of responses! The true highest level of satisfaction service according to my third graph is Quality/experience dr. which had a bad percentage of 42% compared to a good percentage of 46%. I consider this service to be the highest level of satisfaction as it is the only service where the good percentage is greater than the bad.
